<subSubSection id="189D6519FFD679702ADAFEC1FE45D494" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="50383692FFD679702ADAFEC1FF32D40B" blockId="7.[155,794,163,743]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicName id="97874D11FFD679702ADAFEC1FEF3D736" authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[179,313,303,325]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sousae">
<emphasis id="62F3EA80FFD679702ADAFEC1FEF3D736" box="[179,313,303,325]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Solanum sousae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName id="97874D11FFD679702822FEC1FD31D736" authority="Lam." authorityName="Lam." box="[587,763,303,325]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pyrifolium">
<emphasis id="62F3EA80FFD679702822FEC1FD71D736" box="[587,699,303,325]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">S. pyrifolium</emphasis>
Lam.
</taxonomicName>
of Hispaniola, but differs from that species in its more broadly triangular inflorescence outline (
<figureCitation id="C8BC2A17FFD679702B82FE89FDF1D70E" box="[491,571,359,381]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="6.[155,220,1191,1210]" captionTargetBox="[161,999,168,1152]" captionTargetId="figure-447@6.[155,1006,162,1158]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 5. Solanum sousae. A) portion of stem with flowering inflorescence, B) flower, C) flower cross section, D) anthers, E) portion of stem with fruiting inflorecence. A–D drawn from Ventura 2212, E from Maya J. 3938. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0010502.g005" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6517453" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6517453/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
), minute calyx lobes without thickened margins (
<figureCitation id="C8BC2A17FFD679702BC0FE6DFE27D7EA" box="[425,493,387,409]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="6.[155,220,1191,1210]" captionTargetBox="[161,999,168,1152]" captionTargetId="figure-447@6.[155,1006,162,1158]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 5. Solanum sousae. A) portion of stem with flowering inflorescence, B) flower, C) flower cross section, D) anthers, E) portion of stem with fruiting inflorecence. A–D drawn from Ventura 2212, E from Maya J. 3938. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0010502.g005" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6517453" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6517453/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
) and in its lack of a prominent submarginal leaf vein. The leaf pubescence of the two species is very similar, but 
<taxonomicName id="97874D11FFD679702B28FE54FE46D7A3" authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[321,396,442,464]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sousae">
<emphasis id="62F3EA80FFD679702B28FE54FE46D7A3" box="[321,396,442,464]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">S. sousae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in general more densely pubescent on the new growth and abaxial corolla surfaces. 
<taxonomicName id="97874D11FFD67970283CFE38FD1CD79F" authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[597,726,470,492]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sousae">
<emphasis id="62F3EA80FFD67970283CFE38FD1CD79F" box="[597,726,470,492]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Solanum sousae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the more common and sympatric 
<taxonomicName id="97874D11FFD679702849FE1CFD28D47B" authority="Poir." authorityName="Poir." box="[544,738,498,520]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dulcamaroides">
<emphasis id="62F3EA80FFD679702849FE1CFD66D47B" box="[544,684,498,520]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">S. dulcamaroides</emphasis>
Poir.
</taxonomicName>
in its white flowers, generally simple pubescence (versus more commonly dendritic in 
<taxonomicName id="97874D11FFD679702B59FDC7FE77D44C" authorityName="Poir." box="[304,445,553,575]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dulcamaroides">
<emphasis id="62F3EA80FFD679702B59FDC7FE77D44C" box="[304,445,553,575]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">S. dulcamaroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), white rather than purple flowers, and in its anthers that are not markedly thickened and rounded abaxially.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="50383692FFD679702ADAFD90FE45D494" blockId="7.[155,794,163,743]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
It is likely that the juvenile leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="97874D11FFD679702876FD93FDA1D4E0" authorityName="S. Knapp" authorityYear="2010" box="[543,619,637,659]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sousae">
<emphasis id="62F3EA80FFD679702876FD93FDA1D4E0" box="[543,619,637,659]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">S. sousae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are pinnatifid, as are those of most other species in this group; young foliage is only very rarely collected and is often not associated with the flowering stems with simple leaves.
</paragraph>
